    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1899-07-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1899-07-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="605"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d605">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Jackson</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy of the United States.</hi>
                            <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1899-07-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 18, 1899</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(Mr. Jackson reports that Mr. Hay’s telegram of the 17th instant was communicated
                    to the acting secretary of state for foreign affairs. No complaint, Baron
                    Richthofen says, has been made by Belgium, whose Government was some time ago
                    informed that if American cattle were admitted into Belgium prohibitory decrees
                    would be issued. The German Government maintains that, so far as we are
                    concerned, there is no change in the situation. So long as the direct
                    importation of American beef is prohibited, its indirect importation could not
                    be permitted. Mr. Jackson requested that his representations be considered as
                    applying to the general question.)</p>
            </div>
